description.narrative: Output 4.1: The health system at all levels have strengthened organisational capacities and systems to provide services for prevention and treatment of HIV in women, children, adolescents and young people, including in emergencies, which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Hiv Prevention, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: OUTCOME 4: Children, adolescents and women, particularly in high HIV-burden states have increased access to and use quality services to prevent and treat HIV

description.narrative: Prevention of Mother-to-Child Transmission of HIV in Nigeria is receiving more attention following a national dialogue chaired by the Honourable Minister of Health. Improved access to EID and VL services increased EID from 21% in 2020 to 35% in 2021 in Kaduna state. More robust community engagement and collaboration with mentor mothers (MM) in Kaduna and Rivers state increased demand for HIV testing services amongst pregnant and breastfeeding mothers. Also, 95% of HIV-positive pregnant and breastfeeding women received lifelong access to ART for PMTCT in UNICEF-supported Local Government Areas (LGAs) in Kaduna and Rivers states. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:29/12/2021
